Radiation therapy is commonly used in the metastatic setting to palliate pain, 
neurological deficits, bleeding and other complications of metastatic disease, 
allowing patients to live longer and have better quality of life. Despite the 
effective use of radiation and other palliative treatment modalities, many 
patients continue to experience poorly controlled pain and other serious 
sequelae of their disease, underscoring the need for additional research in this 
